data.name: ShutterOpenCloseTimeSeconds.ToolTip
data.value:
The maximum time that the shutter motor should be allowed to run before an error condition is assumed.
This value should be chosen to be 110% to 150% of the time needed to fully open or close the shutter.

data.name: FullRotationTimeSeconds.ToolTip
data.value:
The maximum time that the rotatior motor should be allowed to run before an error condition is assumed.
This value should be chosen to be 110% to 150% of the time needed for a full 360° rotation.

data.name: PresetHD10.ToolTip
data.value:
Safety timeouts limit the time that motors can run before an error condition is assumed.
This preset uses longer than normal safety timeouts. This choice is appropriate if you have had to reduce your motor speeds, increase ramp time, or are using the NexDome motors on a nonstandard observatory.

data.name: ParkAzimuth.ToolTip
data.value: Park Azimuth is the azimuth (in degrees) measured clockwise fromTrue North, where the shutter charging contacts align with the battery charger. Issuing the Park command rotates to the park azimuth then closes the shutter.

data.name: checkBox1.ToolTip
data.value:
Ensure that the Status Windows is Always Visible on one of the currently available monitors.
Default: disabled
Enable this if you find that the status window gets "lost". This can happen if you access your observatory computer remotely from a system that has more or larger monitors.

data.name: ShutterLowVoltsThreshold.ToolTip
data.value:
Sets the threshold (in Volts) for low battery condition in the shutter.
This value will need to be determined by experiment. Different types of battery chemistry can have significantly different discharge curves, and it is impossible to provide any single "coorect" value for this setting. It is up to you, the user, to determine the correct value for your installation. Do not simply use a value that someone has given you as the best value will most likely be different for every installation.
Keep in mind that inherent variation in electrical components might mean that the actual battery voltage may differ by as much as 5% from the measured voltage.
According to batteryuniversity.com, a lead-acid battery is fully charged at 13.2 Volts and should not be discharged below 10.5 Volts. You will need to set the threshold somewhat above 10.5 Volts to allow enough reserve current to close the shutter fully.
Discharging batteries below their minimum voltage can result in permanent damage to the battery.

data.name: EnableShutterAutoClose.ToolTip
data.value:
Configures the shutter to auto-close on low battery volts.
Enable this option if you want the shutter to auto-close. You must also configure the low volts threshold.
Default: disabled
NOTE: it is the shutter firmware (not the driver) that decides if and when to auto-close. This setting only determines whether the ASCOM driver will configure that feature in the shutter.

data.name: ShutterWaitUNtilReady.ToolTip
data.value:
On connecting, wait until the shutter is online and ready before returning.
default: disabled
Some applications may need this enabled if they detect a shutter error on startup. If your application or workflow doesn't require this, leave it off.
